  <body>
      <p>Schiff bases have attracted overwhelming attention from many researchers owing to their importance in exhibiting thermochromism and photochromism [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B1-molbank-2010-M686">1</xref>,<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B2-molbank-2010-M686">2</xref>,<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B3-molbank-2010-M686">3</xref>,<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B4-molbank-2010-M686">4</xref>,<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B5-molbank-2010-M686">5</xref>]. The presence of a long alkyl chain at the <italic>para</italic> position of the aldehyde or aniline fragment of <italic>N</italic>-benzylideneanilines has been regarded as one of the important elements which favours the existence of liquid crystal phases [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B6-molbank-2010-M686">6</xref>,<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B7-molbank-2010-M686">7</xref>,<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B8-molbank-2010-M686">8</xref>]. Different alkyl chain length can significantly influence the anisotropic properties of liquid crystals [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B6-molbank-2010-M686">6</xref>]. Thus, we report here another new derivative containing an octadecanoyloxy chain, 3-hydroxy-4-{[(4-methoxyphenyl)imino]methyl}phenyl octadecanoate.</p>
